36,"icon":353,"size":338,"hiddenText":13},{"text":351,"url":352,"target":80,"ariaLabel":28},"Frontiers Instagram","https://www.instagram.com/frontiersin_","Instagram","Frontiers Media SA. All rights reserved.","https://www.frontiersin.org/legal/terms-and-conditions","https://www.frontiersin.org/legal/privacy-policy","https://www.frontiersin.org/about/accessibility-statement",{},false,{"__typename":361,"identifier":118,"name":119,"slug":120,"banner":362,"description":406,"mission":407,"palette":408,"impactFactor":409,"citeScore":410,"citations":411,"showTagline":28,"twitter":412},"Journal",[363],{"id":364,"src":365,"name":366,"type":367,"width":368,"height":369,"idHash":370,"archive":371,"brandId":372,"limited":371,"fileSize":373,"isPublic":118,"original":374,"copyright":19,"extension":375,"thumbnails":377,"dateCreated":385,"description":19,"orientation":386,"userCreated":387,"watermarked":371,"dateModified":385,"datePublished":388,"ecsArchiveFiles":389,"propertyOptions":390,"property_Channel":395,"property_Sub-Type":397,"property_Asset_Type":399,"activeOriginalFocusPoint":401,"property_Office_Department":404},"27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4","https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/E32629C6-9347-4F84-81FEAEF7BFA342B3/27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4/webimage-731DCAD7-7D53-4C7A-ABED6B270359A65F.png","FNINS_Main Visual_Purple_Website","image",6788,4865,"18e4eb8ad56b508b",0,"22C10171-81B3-4DA6-99342F272A32E8BB",12200641,"https://brand.frontiersin.org/m/18e4eb8ad56b508b/original/FNINS_Main-Visual_Purple_Website.jpg",[376],"jpg",{"mini":378,"thul":379,"webimage":365,"Guidelines":380,"WebsiteJpg_XL":381,"WebsiteWebP_L":382,"WebsiteWebP_M":383,"WebsiteWebP_XL":384},"https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/E32629C6-9347-4F84-81FEAEF7BFA342B3/27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4/mini-64E6EA95-B7B1-4005-AB72061E18A6F830.png","https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/E32629C6-9347-4F84-81FEAEF7BFA342B3/27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4/thul-38432C11-11F0-4DA5-B8C0EBF0A1603722.png","https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/E32629C6-9347-4F84-81FEAEF7BFA342B3/27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4/A72D78D9-73CD-4C75-910FB7C0D04825C0/Guidelines-FNINS_Main Visual_Purple_Website.png","https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/E32629C6-9347-4F84-81FEAEF7BFA342B3/27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4/A72D78D9-73CD-4C75-910FB7C0D04825C0/WebsiteJpg_XL-FNINS_Main Visual_Purple_Website.jpg","https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/E32629C6-9347-4F84-81FEAEF7BFA342B3/27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4/A72D78D9-73CD-4C75-910FB7C0D04825C0/WebsiteWebP_L-FNINS_Main Visual_Purple_Website.webp","https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/E32629C6-9347-4F84-81FEAEF7BFA342B3/27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4/A72D78D9-73CD-4C75-910FB7C0D04825C0/WebsiteWebP_M-FNINS_Main Visual_Purple_Website.webp","https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/E32629C6-9347-4F84-81FEAEF7BFA342B3/27A044CC-44D1-4E5E-A886893A3FE656F4/A72D78D9-73CD-4C75-910FB7C0D04825C0/WebsiteWebP_XL-FNINS_Main Visual_Purple_Website.webp","2022-06-27T10:00:29Z","landscape","Caroline Sutter","2022-06-27T09:27:09Z",[],[391,392,393,394],"414FB2D4-2283-43FD-BE14E534ECA67928","6C18119B-14BD-4951-B437696F4357BD33","7C692885-DB25-4858-B1FB4FF47B241E9B","D88C0047-EC30-4506-A7DF28A4D765E1CF",[396],"frontiersin_org",[398],"Main_Visual",[400],"Photography",{"x":402,"y":403},3394,2433,[405],"Publishing","Explore open access research in neuroscience, covering brain structure, function and disorders from cells to systems and behavior.","\u003Cp>Frontiers in Neuroscience is a leading multidisciplinary journal that publishes research across a wide range of spectrum of specialities and disciplines in the field of neuroscience.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Led by Field Chief Editor, Professor Idan Segev (Hebrew University of Jerusalem, Israel) and indexed in PubMed Central (PMC), Web of Science (SCIE), and Scopus among others, the journal provides a comprehensive understanding of brain functions, from genes to behavior, and aims to tighten the links between various domains of neuroscience and advance conceptual and technological developments in the field.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Topics of interest include, but are not limited to:\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>autonomic function and brain energy homeostasis\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>neural development and degeneration\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>neuroengineering including neuromorphic engineering and neuroprosthetics\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>novel brain imaging methods from the subcellular level (e.g. genetically encoded voltage- and ions indicators) to the whole brain level (e.g. large-scale micro-electrode arrays and direct imaging of neuronal activity at the cellular level by fMRI)\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>sensory perception and cognition.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>translational neuroscience\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Cp>Studies on the convergence of novel molecular and optical techniques, and developments in anatomical methods, both at the whole-brain level (“connectome”) and the local circuit and synaptic level (“connectomics”) are of particular interest.  Approaches that allow us to link the structure of local circuits at specific brain regions to function are encouraged.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>The journal also welcomes submissions which support and advance the UN’s Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), notably SDG 3: to ensure healthy lives and promote well-being for all at all ages. Studies that propose ways to promote mental health and prevent neurodegenerative diseases are of particular interest.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Studies that focus on clinical trials, medical treatments, or the application of medical techniques without neuroscientific foundations are not within the scope of the journal. Similarly, studies that primarily investigate the effects of traditional medicine on health conditions, without exploring the underlying neurological mechanisms, fall outside of the journal scope.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Frontiers’ journals require that manuscripts primarily comprising computational studies of public data, must include appropriate validation. Please refer to the \u003Ca href=\"https://www.frontiersin.org/guidelines/policies-and-publication-ethics#standards-for-research-methodology:~:text=complaints%20and%20allegations.-,Standards%20for%20research%20methodology,-Experiments\">Frontiers Standards for research methodology policy\u003C/a>, for more information. Manuscripts not adhering to these standards will not be considered.\u003Cp>\n\n\u003Cp>Frontiers in Neuroscience is committed to advancing developments in the field by allowing unrestricted access to research articles and communicating scientific knowledge to researchers and the public alike, to enhance scientific understanding and repairing the brain.\u003C/p>","purple","4.3","6.8","434523","@FrontNeurosci",{"id":118,"name":119,"slug":120,"abbreviation":414,"isOnline":13,"isOpenForSubmissions":13,"citeScore":415,"impactFactor":416},"fnins",6.6,3.2,{"displayTitlePillLabels":13,"displayRelatedArticlesBox":13,"showEditors":13,"showReviewers":13,"showLoopImpactLink":13,"enableFigshare":359},{"isPublic":359,"allowCompanyUsers":359,"whiteListEmails":419,"enableAllJournals":359,"whiteListJournals":420},[],[],{"spaceId":118,"name":118,"availableJournalPages":422,"announcement":426,"useJournalPalettes":359},[266,271,268,423,424,425],"volumes","about","community-reviewers",{"__typename":427,"sys":428,"preHeader":430,"title":431,"description":432,"image":433,"link":455},"Announcement",{"id":429},"2IPv1l2IAkUt7RUrh3yJzz","Frontiers' quality","How do we build trust in science?","Behind each Frontiers journal is an editorial board committed to upholding research integrity and scientific quality",[434],{"id":435,"src":436,"name":437,"tags":438,"type":367,"width":439,"height":440,"archive":371,"brandId":372,"limited":371,"fileSize":441,"isPublic":371,"original":28,"copyright":28,"extension":442,"thumbnails":444,"dateCreated":451,"description":28,"orientation":386,"watermarked":371,"dateModified":451,"selectedFile":28,"datePublished":452,"videoPreviewURLs":453,"textMetaproperties":454},"1C167ADA-64D7-41F6-B87288EAF1BEC484","https://brand.frontiersin.org/m/47cd35867c2ab214/webimage-Horizontal-Scientist-looking-at-3D-rendered-graphic-scans-from-Magnetic-Resonance-Imaging-MRI-scanner-close-up.png","Horizontal-Scientist looking at 3D rendered graphic scans from Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) scanner, close up",[],1920,1080,2419221,[443],"png",{"mini":445,"thul":446,"webimage":436,"Guidelines":447,"WebsiteJpg_XL":448,"WebsiteWebP_L":449,"WebsiteWebP_M":450},"https://brand.frontiersin.org/m/47cd35867c2ab214/mini-Horizontal-Scientist-looking-at-3D-rendered-graphic-scans-from-Magnetic-Resonance-Imaging-MRI-scanner-close-up.png","https://brand.frontiersin.org/m/47cd35867c2ab214/thul-Horizontal-Scientist-looking-at-3D-rendered-graphic-scans-from-Magnetic-Resonance-Imaging-MRI-scanner-close-up.png","https://brand.frontiersin.org/asset/1c167ada-64d7-41f6-b872-88eaf1bec484/Guidelines/Horizontal-Scientist-looking-at-3D-rendered-graphic-scans-from-Magnetic-Resonance-Imaging-MRI-scanner-close-up.png","https://brand.frontiersin.org/asset/1c167ada-64d7-41f6-b872-88eaf1bec484/WebsiteJpg_XL/Horizontal-Scientist-looking-at-3D-rendered-graphic-scans-from-Magnetic-Resonance-Imaging-MRI-scanner-close-up.jpg","https://brand.frontiersin.org/asset/1c167ada-64d7-41f6-b872-88eaf1bec484/WebsiteWebP_L/Horizontal-Scientist-looking-at-3D-rendered-graphic-scans-from-Magnetic-Resonance-Imaging-MRI-scanner-close-up.webp","https://brand.frontiersin.org/asset/1c167ada-64d7-41f6-b872-88eaf1bec484/WebsiteWebP_M/Horizontal-Scientist-looking-at-3D-rendered-graphic-scans-from-Magnetic-Resonance-Imaging-MRI-scanner-close-up.webp","2026-03-06T11:24:30Z","2026-03-06T11:24:07Z",[],[],{"text":456,"url":457,"target":27,"ariaLabel":28},"Learn more","https://www.frontiersin.org/about/quality",{"loggedUserInfo":-1},{"currentArticle":460,"isPreviewPage":359,"hasSupplementalData":359,"showCrossmarkWidget":13,"articleTemplate":571,"currentArticlePageMetaInfo":572,"xmlParsedArticleContent":679,"xmlParsingError":-1},{"id":461,"doi":462,"title":463,"acceptanceDate":464,"receptionDate":465,"publicationDate":466,"lastModifiedDate":467,"isPublished":13,"abstract":468,"researchTopic":469,"articleType":475,"stage":478,"keywords":480,"authors":486,"editors":502,"reviewers":511,"journal":529,"section":536,"impactMetrics":538,"volume":542,"articleVolume":543,"relatedArticles":544,"isPublishedV2":359,"contents":545,"files":546},637221,"10.3389/fnins.2021.637221","Biologically Relevant Lighting: An Industry Perspective",["Date","2021-05-05T10:38:21.000Z"],["Date","2020-12-04T16:55:06.000Z"],["Date","2021-06-07T00:00:00.000Z"],["Date","2026-04-06T04:56:24.839Z"],"Innovations in LED lighting technology have led to tremendous adoption rates and vastly improved the metrics by which they are traditionally evaluated – including color quality, longevity, and energy efficiency to name a few.  Additionally, scientific insight has broadened with respect to the biological impact of light, specifically our circadian rhythm.  The data shows that indoor electric lighting, despite its many attributes, fails to elicit a proper biological response.  Light levels are biologically too dim during the day, too bright at night, and with many people spending much of their lives in these environments, it can lead to circadian dysfunction. \nThe lighting industry’s biological solution has been to create bluer days and yellower nights, which caters primarily to the visual system.  A better call to action is to provide biologically brighter days and biologically darker nights within the built environment.  However, current lighting design practices have specified the comfort and utility of electric light.  Brighter intensity during the day can often be uncomfortable or glary, and reduced light intensity at night may compromise visual comfort and safety, both of which will affect user compliance.\nNo single lighting solution will effectively create biologically brighter days and biologically darker nights, but rather a variety of parameters need to be considered.  This paper discusses the contributions of spectral power distribution (SPD), hue or color temperature (CCT), spatial distribution, as well as architectural geometry and surface reflectivity, to achieve biologically relevant lighting.",{"id":470,"title":471,"articlesCount":472,"isMagazinePage":13,"slug":473,"isOpenForSubmission":359,"views":474},12871,"Translation and Processing of Light by the Non-Image Forming Visual System – Context, Mechanisms and Applications",17,"translation-and-processing-of-light-by-the-non-image-forming-visual-system---context-mechanisms-and-applications",204599,{"id":476,"name":477},28,"Perspective",{"id":479,"name":19},18,[481,482,483,484,485],"Social jet lag","circadian","Lighting","Melanopsin","Opn4",[487,496],{"id":488,"firstName":489,"middleName":19,"lastName":490,"givenNames":491,"isCorresponding":359,"isProfilePublic":13,"userId":488,"email":-1,"affiliations":492},984526,"Robert","Soler","Robert ",[493],{"organizationName":494,"countryName":495,"cityName":19,"stateName":19,"zipCode":19},"BIOS Lighting","United States",{"id":371,"firstName":497,"middleName":19,"lastName":498,"givenNames":499,"isCorresponding":359,"isProfilePublic":359,"userId":371,"email":-1,"affiliations":500},"Erica","Voss","Erica ",[501],{"organizationName":494,"countryName":495,"cityName":19,"stateName":19,"zipCode":19},[503],{"id":504,"firstName":505,"middleName":19,"lastName":506,"givenNames":507,"isCorresponding":359,"isProfilePublic":13,"userId":504,"email":-1,"affiliations":508},174519,"Jamie","Zeitzer","Jamie ",[509],{"organizationName":510,"countryName":495,"cityName":19,"stateName":19,"zipCode":19},"Stanford University",[512,521],{"id":513,"firstName":514,"middleName":515,"lastName":516,"givenNames":517,"isCorresponding":359,"isProfilePublic":13,"userId":513,"email":-1,"affiliations":518},601538,"Daniel","S.","Joyce","Daniel  S.",[519],{"organizationName":520,"countryName":495,"cityName":19,"stateName":19,"zipCode":19},"University of Nevada, Reno",{"id":522,"firstName":523,"middleName":19,"lastName":524,"givenNames":525,"isCorresponding":359,"isProfilePublic":13,"userId":522,"email":-1,"affiliations":526},1112982,"Michael","Herf","Michael ",[527],{"organizationName":528,"countryName":495,"cityName":19,"stateName":19,"zipCode":19},"Other",{"id":118,"slug":120,"name":119,"shortName":530,"electronicISSN":531,"field":532,"specialtyId":28,"journalSectionPaths":534},"Front. Neurosci.","1662-453X",{"id":533,"domainId":118},55,[535],{"section":536},{"id":191,"name":192,"slug":193,"specialtyId":537},1852,{"views":539,"downloads":540,"citations":541},8358,2061,10,15,"Volume 15 - 2021",[],{"titleHtml":19,"fullTextHtml":19,"menuHtml":19},[547,552,558,561,567],{"name":548,"fileServerPackageEntryId":19,"fileServerId":549,"fileServerVersionNumber":118,"type":550},"EPUB.epub","637221/epub",{"code":551,"name":551},"EPUB",{"name":553,"fileServerPackageEntryId":554,"fileServerId":555,"fileServerVersionNumber":118,"type":556},"fnins-15-637221.pdf","fnins-15-637221/fnins-15-637221.pdf","637221/pubmed-zip",{"code":557,"name":557},"PDF",{"name":553,"fileServerPackageEntryId":19,"fileServerId":559,"fileServerVersionNumber":118,"type":560},"637221/publishers-proof/pdf",{"code":557,"name":557},{"name":562,"fileServerPackageEntryId":563,"fileServerId":555,"fileServerVersionNumber":118,"type":564},"fnins-15-637221.xml","fnins-15-637221/fnins-15-637221.xml",{"code":565,"name":566},"NLM_XML","XML",{"name":568,"fileServerPackageEntryId":19,"fileServerId":569,"fileServerVersionNumber":118,"type":570},"Provisional PDF.pdf","637221/provisional-pdf",{"code":557,"name":557},"v4",{"title":573,"link":574,"meta":578,"script":667},"Frontiers | Biologically Relevant Lighting: An Industry Perspective",[575],{"rel":576,"href":577},"canonical","https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/neuroscience/articles/10.3389/fnins.2021.637221/full",[579,582,585,587,590,594,597,601,604,607,610,612,614,616,618,620,623,626,628,631,634,636,639,642,645,648,651,655,659,662,664],{"hid":580,"property":580,"name":580,"content":581},"description","Innovations in LED lighting technology have led to tremendous adoption rates and vastly improved the metrics by which they are traditionally evaluated – incl...",{"hid":583,"property":583,"name":584,"content":573},"og:title","title",{"hid":586,"property":586,"name":580,"content":581},"og:description",{"hid":588,"name":588,"content":589},"keywords","Social jet lag,circadian,Lighting,Melanopsin,Opn4",{"hid":591,"property":591,"name":592,"content":593},"og:site_name","site_name","Frontiers",{"hid":595,"property":595,"name":367,"content":596},"og:image","https://images-provider.frontiersin.org/api/ipx/w=1200&f=png/https://www.frontiersin.org/files/Articles/637221/fnins-15-637221-HTML/image_m/fnins-15-637221-g001.jpg",{"hid":598,"property":598,"name":599,"content":600},"og:type","type","article",{"hid":602,"property":602,"name":603,"content":577},"og:url","url",{"hid":605,"name":605,"content":606},"twitter:card","summary_large_image",{"hid":608,"name":608,"content":609},"citation_volume","15",{"hid":611,"name":611,"content":119},"citation_journal_title",{"hid":613,"name":613,"content":593},"citation_publisher",{"hid":615,"name":615,"content":530},"citation_journal_abbrev",{"hid":617,"name":617,"content":531},"citation_issn",{"hid":619,"name":619,"content":462},"citation_doi",{"hid":621,"name":621,"content":622},"citation_firstpage","637221",{"hid":624,"name":624,"content":625},"citation_language","English",{"hid":627,"name":627,"content":463},"citation_title",{"hid":629,"name":629,"content":630},"citation_keywords","Social jet lag; circadian; Lighting; Melanopsin; Opn4",{"hid":632,"name":632,"content":633},"citation_abstract","Innovations in LED lighting technology have led to tremendous adoption rates and vastly improved the metrics by which they are traditionally evaluated – including color quality, longevity, and energy efficiency to name a few.  Additionally, scientific insight has broadened with respect to the biological impact of light, specifically our circadian rhythm.  The data shows that indoor electric lighting, despite its many attributes, fails to elicit a proper biological response.  Light levels are biologically too dim during the day, too bright at night, and with many people spending much of their lives in these environments, it can lead to circadian dysfunction. The lighting industry’s biological solution has been to create bluer days and yellower nights, which caters primarily to the visual system.  A better call to action is to provide biologically brighter days and biologically darker nights within the built environment.  However, current lighting design practices have specified the comfort and utility of electric light.  Brighter intensity during the day can often be uncomfortable or glary, and reduced light intensity at night may compromise visual comfort and safety, both of which will affect user compliance.No single lighting solution will effectively create biologically brighter days and biologically darker nights, but rather a variety of parameters need to be considered.  This paper discusses the contributions of spectral power distribution (SPD), hue or color temperature (CCT), spatial distribution, as well as architectural geometry and surface reflectivity, to achieve biologically relevant lighting.",{"hid":635,"name":635,"content":477},"citation_article_type",{"hid":637,"name":637,"content":638},"citation_pdf_url","https://public-pages-files-2025.frontiersin.org/journals/neuroscience/articles/10.3389/fnins.2021.637221/pdf",{"hid":640,"name":640,"content":641},"citation_xml_url","https://public-pages-files-2025.frontiersin.org/journals/neuroscience/articles/10.3389/fnins.2021.637221/xml",{"hid":643,"name":643,"content":644},"citation_fulltext_world_readable","yes",{"hid":646,"name":646,"content":647},"citation_online_date","2021/05/05",{"hid":649,"name":649,"content":650},"citation_publication_date","2021/06/07",{"hid":652,"name":653,"content":654},"citation_author_0","citation_author","Soler, Robert ",{"hid":656,"name":657,"content":658},"citation_author_institution_0","citation_author_institution","BIOS Lighting, United States",{"hid":660,"name":653,"content":661},"citation_author_1","Voss, Erica ",{"hid":663,"name":657,"content":658},"citation_author_institution_1",{"hid":665,"name":665,"content":666},"dc.identifier","doi:10.3389/fnins.2021.637221",[668,671,673,675,677],{"src":669,"body":13,"type":670,"async":13},"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/polyfill/v3/polyfill.min.js?features=es6","text/javascript",{"src":672,"body":13,"type":670,"async":13},"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/mathjax/2.7.1/MathJax.js?config=TeX-MML-AM_CHTML",{"src":674,"body":13,"type":670,"async":13},"https://d1bxh8uas1mnw7.cloudfront.net/assets/altmetric_badges-f0bc9b243ff5677d05460c1eb71834ca998946d764eb3bc244ab4b18ba50d21e.js",{"src":676,"body":13,"type":670,"async":13},"https://api.altmetric.com/v1/doi/10.3389/fnins.2021.637221?callback=_altmetric.embed_callback&domain=www.frontiersin.org&key=3c130976ca2b8f2e88f8377633751ba1&cache_until=14-15",{"src":678,"body":13,"type":670,"async":13},"https://crossmark-cdn.crossref.org/widget/v2.0/widget.js",{"journal":680,"doi":462,"articleType":477,"title":682,"authors":684,"onBehalfOf":19,"affiliations":690,"authorNotes":694,"publicationDate":728,"acceptedDate":729,"receivedDate":730,"correctedDate":19,"retractedDate":19,"volume":542,"elocationId":461,"permissions":731,"keywords":751,"relatedArticles":765,"abstractContent":766,"bodyContent":774,"appendixContent":3231,"statements":3232,"references":3736,"otherBackSections":7769,"figures":7770,"toc":7971,"correspondingAuthors":7993},{"title":119,"abbreviation":530,"issn":531,"publisherName":681},"Frontiers Media S.A.",[683],{"#text":463},[685,688],{"surname":490,"givenNames":489,"suffix":19,"affiliationsIndexes":686,"isCorresponding":13,"equalContrib":359,"hierarchySymbol":19,"footnoteSymbol":19,"loopUrl":687,"onBehalfOf":19},[],"http://loop.frontiersin.org/people/984526/overview",{"surname":498,"givenNames":497,"suffix":19,"affiliationsIndexes":689,"isCorresponding":359,"equalContrib":359,"hierarchySymbol":19,"footnoteSymbol":19,"loopUrl":19,"onBehalfOf":19},[],[691],{"index":371,"baseText":19,"institution":494,"country":495,"address":692,"textContent":693},"Carlsbad, CA","BIOS Lighting, Carlsbad, CA, United States",{"editedBy":695,"editedByContent":698,"reviewedBy":707,"reviewedByContent":710,"approvedBy":717,"approvedByContent":718,"correspondence":719,"equalContribution":720,"presentAddress":19,"other":721},[696],{"textContent":697},"Edited by: Jamie Zeitzer, Stanford University, United States",[699,701,705],{"#text":700},"\n          ",{"p":702},[703],{"#text":704}," Jamie Zeitzer, Stanford University, United States",{"#text":706},"\n        ",[708],{"textContent":709},"Reviewed by: Michael Herf, f.lux Software LLC, United States; Daniel S. Joyce, University of Nevada, Reno, United States",[711,712,716],{"#text":700},{"p":713},[714],{"#text":715}," Michael Herf, f.lux Software LLC, United States; Daniel S. Joyce, University of Nevada, Reno, United States",{"#text":706},[],[],"*Correspondence: Robert Soler, cnNvbGVyQGJpb3NsaWdodGluZy5jb20=",[],[722,723,727],{"#text":700},{"p":724},[725],{"#text":726},"This article was submitted to Sleep and Circadian Rhythms, a section of the journal Frontiers in Neuroscience",{"#text":706},"2021-06-07","2021-05-05","2020-12-04",{"copyrightStatement":732,"copyrightYear":733,"copyrightHolder":734,"licenseUrl":735,"licenseText":736},"Copyright © 2021 Soler and Voss.",2021,"Soler and Voss","http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/",[737,738,750],{"#text":700},{"p":739},[740,742,748],{"#text":741},"This is an open-access article distributed under the terms of the ",{"ext-link":743,":@":746},[744],{"#text":745},"Creative Commons Attribution License (CC BY)",{"@_ext-link-type":747,"@_xlink:href":735},"uri",{"#text":749},". The use, distribution or reproduction in other forums is permitted, provided the original author(s) and the copyright owner(s) are credited and that the original publication in this journal is cited, in accordance with accepted academic practice. No use, distribution or reproduction is permitted which does not comply with these terms.",{"#text":706},[752,755,757,760,763],[753],{"#text":754},"social jet lag",[756],{"#text":482},[758],{"#text":759},"lighting",[761],{"#text":762},"melanopsin",[764],{"#text":485},[],[767,768,772],{"#text":706},{"p":769},[770],{"#text":771},"Innovations in LED lighting technology have led to tremendous adoption rates and vastly improved the metrics by which they are traditionally evaluated–including color quality, longevity, and energy efficiency to name a few. Additionally, scientific insight has broadened with respect to the biological impact of light, specifically our circadian rhythm. Indoor electric lighting, despite its many attributes, fails to specifically address the biological responses to light. Traditional electric lighting environments are biologically too dim during the day, too bright at night, and with many people spending much of their lives in these environments, it can lead to circadian dysfunction. The lighting industry’s biological solution has been to create bluer days and yellower nights, but the technology created to do so caters primarily to the cones. A better call to action is to provide biologically brighter days and biologically darker nights within the built environment. However, current lighting design practices have specified the comfort and utility of electric light. Brighter intensity during the day can often be uncomfortable or glary, and reduced light intensity at night may compromise visual comfort and safety, both of which will affect user compliance. No single lighting solution will effectively create biologically brighter days and biologically darker nights, but rather a variety of parameters need to be considered. This paper discusses the contributions of spectral power distribution, hue or color temperature, spatial distribution, as well as architectural geometry and surface reflectivity, to achieve biologically relevant lighting.",{"#text":773},"\n      ",[775,777,1021,1022,1073,1074,2547,2548,2905,2906,2921,2922,2943,2944,3180,3181,3196,3197,3212,3213,3229],{"#text":776},"\n    ",{"sec":778,":@":1019},[779,780,784,785,929,930,999,1000,1018],{"#text":773},{"title":781},[782],{"#text":783},"Introduction",{"#text":773},{"p":786},[787,789,796,798,804,805,811,812,818,819,825,826,832,833,839,840,846,847,853,855,859,861,867,869,875,876,882,883,889,890,896,897,903,905,911,913,919,921,927],{"#text":788},"The discovery of a novel Intrinsically Photosenstive Retinal Ganglion Cell (ipRGC) in the eye has changed our understanding of the role of light in our everyday lives (",{"xref":790,":@":793},[791],{"#text":792},"Provencio and Foster, 1995",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":795},"bibr","B27",{"#text":797},"; ",{"xref":799,":@":802},[800],{"#text":801},"Provencio et al., 1998",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":803},"B26",{"#text":797},{"xref":806,":@":809},[807],{"#text":808},"Brainard et al., 2001",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":810},"B4",{"#text":797},{"xref":813,":@":816},[814],{"#text":815},"Thapan et al., 2001",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":817},"B37",{"#text":797},{"xref":820,":@":823},[821],{"#text":822},"Berson et al., 2002",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":824},"B3",{"#text":797},{"xref":827,":@":830},[828],{"#text":829},"Panda et al., 2002",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":831},"B24",{"#text":797},{"xref":834,":@":837},[835],{"#text":836},"Dacey et al., 2005",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":838},"B7",{"#text":797},{"xref":841,":@":844},[842],{"#text":843},"Güler et al., 2008",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":845},"B11",{"#text":797},{"xref":848,":@":851},[849],{"#text":850},"Hughes et al., 2016",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":852},"B12",{"#text":854},"). These ipRGCs contain a photopigment melanopsin with an ",{"italic":856},[857],{"#text":858},"in-vitro",{"#text":860}," spectral sensitivity around 480 nm. However, after lens transmission this spectral sensitivity is shifted to longer wavelengths between 487 and 496 nm (",{"xref":862,":@":865},[863],{"#text":864},"Spitschan, 2019",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":866},"B34",{"#text":868},"), and it is now understood that these ipRGCs are responsible for several physiological effects such as circadian synchronization, tracking seasonal changes, acute alertness, working memory improvements and mood improvements (",{"xref":870,":@":873},[871],{"#text":872},"Gaggioni et al., 2014",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":874},"B10",{"#text":797},{"xref":877,":@":880},[878],{"#text":879},"LeGates et al., 2014",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":881},"B15",{"#text":797},{"xref":884,":@":887},[885],{"#text":886},"Rodgers et al., 2016",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":888},"B29",{"#text":797},{"xref":891,":@":894},[892],{"#text":893},"Fernandez et al., 2018",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":895},"B8",{"#text":797},{"xref":898,":@":901},[899],{"#text":900},"Brown, 2020",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":902},"B5",{"#text":904},"). The role of rods and cones on ipRGC response is still being debated. Some studies have shown no contribution of S-cone (",{"xref":906,":@":909},[907],{"#text":908},"Spitschan et al., 2019",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":910},"B35",{"#text":912},") while others show an exposure time dependent contribution of S-cone (",{"xref":914,":@":917},[915],{"#text":916},"Brown et al., 2021",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":918},"B6",{"#text":920},") when evaluating melatonin suppression. Further studies show a reduced circadian impact of blue colored environments (",{"xref":922,":@":925},[923],{"#text":924},"Mouland et al., 2019",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":926},"B19",{"#text":928},"). Less information is available on rod and cone contributions for other ipRGC driven responses.",{"#text":773},{"p":931},[932,934,940,942,948,950,956,957,963,964,968,969,975,977,981,983,989,991,997],{"#text":933},"In order to apply a biologically relevant lighting solution within the built environment, we must first understand the challenge at hand. Today, we spend most of our time indoors, removed from daylight which contains an important natural and robust daytime and nighttime signal (",{"xref":935,":@":938},[936],{"#text":937},"Knoop et al., 2020",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":939},"B14",{"#text":941},"). Daylight has been replaced with electric lighting which has been engineered and optimized for visual efficiency and can be switched on or off at any time of the day. Moreover, today’s light level recommendations (while sufficient for visual tasks) are insufficient for proper circadian signaling. We find ourselves immersed in environments where the lighting is too biologically dim for our brains to receive a proper daytime signal and too biologically bright to provide a proper nighttime signal. This lack of delineation between day and night can lead to circadian drift and exacerbate social jet lag (",{"xref":943,":@":946},[944],{"#text":945},"Roenneberg and Merrow, 2016",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":947},"B31",{"#text":949},"), which have been associated with a whole host of negative health outcomes: decreases in learning and attention, increased risk of obesity, addiction, and cardiovascular disease (",{"xref":951,":@":954},[952],{"#text":953},"Roenneberg et al., 2012",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":955},"B30",{"#text":797},{"xref":958,":@":961},[959],{"#text":960},"Zarrinpar et al., 2015",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":962},"B39",{"#text":797},{"xref":965,":@":967},[966],{"#text":945},{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":947},{"#text":797},{"xref":970,":@":973},[971],{"#text":972},"Sulli et al., 2018",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":974},"B36",{"#text":976},"). Moreover, this appears to be a widespread phenomenon that affects the majority of people. In fact, it has been shown that 87% of non-shift workers have some form of circadian dysfunction and the associated health risks previously mentioned (",{"xref":978,":@":980},[979],{"#text":945},{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":947},{"#text":982},"), illustrating that the current lighting environment may be insufficient for proper circadian entrainment and amplitude. Therefore, biologically relevant lighting should provide biologically brighter days and biologically darker nights within the built environment. However, in practice there are additional constraints. Energy consumption, visual comfort (i.e., glare) associated with brighter days, and visual acuity and safety related to darker nights. It should be noted that while everyone should benefit from brighter days and darker nights, it may not be additive, there may be more benefit from darker nights compared to brighter days (",{"xref":984,":@":987},[985],{"#text":986},"Skeldon et al., 2017",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":988},"B33",{"#text":990},"), and vice versa, depending on existing conditions and population type. We do know that large differences exist between individuals for nighttime melatonin suppression (",{"xref":992,":@":995},[993],{"#text":994},"Phillips et al., 2019",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":996},"B25",{"#text":998},").",{"#text":773},{"p":1001},[1002,1004,1010,1011,1017],{"#text":1003},"In order to create truly biologically relevant lighting, the following factors must be considered in conjunction with one another: spectral composition, color, intensity, and distribution of the light, as well as the geometry and reflectivity of the built environment. As long as we remain in the built environment, there is no single strategy that can provide the optimum circadian lighting environment. Instead, we must use a multi-faceted approach to achieve biologically relevant lighting that is focused on biologically brighter days and darker nights. Ultimately, we need to understand how both circadian lighting factors and visual lighting factors can be addressed to create spaces that are both biologically relevant for day and night while still providing comfortable and well-designed spaces (",{"xref":1005,":@":1008},[1006],{"#text":1007},"Berman et al., 1991",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":1009},"B2",{"#text":797},{"xref":1012,":@":1015},[1013],{"#text":1014},"Rea and Ouellette, 1991",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":1016},"B28",{"#text":998},{"#text":776},{"@_id":1020},"S1",{"#text":776},{"sec":1023,":@":1071},[1024,1025,1029,1030,1045,1046,1070],{"#text":773},{"title":1026},[1027],{"#text":1028},"Current Industry Standards, Metrics and Recommendations",{"#text":773},{"p":1031},[1032,1034,1038,1040,1043],{"#text":1033},"The WELL Building Standard",{"sup":1035},[1036],{"#text":1037},"TM",{"#text":1039}," uses a series of design categories–Air, Water, Nourishment, Light, Movement, Thermal Comfort, Sound, Materials, Mind, Community, and Innovation–to create a point-based framework that determines how much wellness can be delivered to building occupants. A minimum of 40 points is required to achieve any type of WELL certification, with nine total points available from the Light concept. Circadian lighting and daylight exposure are key Features within the WELL",{"sup":1041},[1042],{"#text":1037},{"#text":1044}," “Light” concept. The Circadian Lighting Design Feature uses vertical melanopic equivalent daylight illuminance (EDI) as a criterion for minimum daytime circadian stimulus. Vertical melanopic EDI is measured based on the occupants’ primary location within a space. Circadian light level measurements are meant to quantify the light reaching the occupants’ eye and as such are taken 4′ above finished floor (or 18″ above the task plane) in the primary viewing direction of the occupant. The amount of vertical melanopic EDI required is dependent on how much daylight availability there is. It ranges from 109 vertical melanopic EDI (for one point) when adequate daylight is present to 218 vertical melanopic EDI (for three points) when sufficient daylight is not present.",{"#text":773},{"p":1047},[1048,1050,1054,1056,1062,1063,1069],{"#text":1049},"Melanopic EDI originated from The International Commission on Illumination (CIE) issuance of the CIE S 026/E:2018, and uses the same melanopic sensitivity function as the Lucas toolbox, with peak sensitivity at 490 nm. Additionally, the CIE has proposed melanopic Daylight Efficiency Ratio (melanopic DER) as a metric for determining the biological potential for a light spectrum to activate melanopsin relative to visual illuminance (lumens/m",{"sup":1051},[1052],{"#text":1053},"2",{"#text":1055},") (",{"xref":1057,":@":1060},[1058],{"#text":1059},"Lucas et al., 2014",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":1061},"B17",{"#text":797},{"xref":1064,":@":1067},[1065],{"#text":1066},"International Commission on Illumination, 2018",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":1068},"B13",{"#text":998},{"#text":776},{"@_id":1072},"S2",{"#text":776},{"sec":1075,":@":2545},[1076,1077,1081,1082,1110,1111,2007,2008,2084,2085,2471,2472,2544],{"#text":773},{"title":1078},[1079],{"#text":1080},"The Role of Led Technology in Biologically Relevant Lighting",{"#text":773},{"p":1083},[1084,1086,1092,1094,1100,1102,1108],{"#text":1085},"Light emitting diodes (LEDs) lighting has seen tremendous adoption rates due to its energy efficiency and longevity. As of 2018 residential products saw LED penetration in 33% of A-lamps and 45% of recessed downlights, while office lighting saw LED penetration in 20% of linear installations (",{"xref":1087,":@":1090},[1088],{"#text":1089},"Navigant, 2019",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":1091},"B21",{"#text":1093},", ",{"xref":1095,":@":1098},[1096],{"#text":1097},"2020",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":1099},"B22",{"#text":1101},"). How does LED lighting impact these newly discovered physiological responses to light? Some claim that LEDs contain a large blue peak, sending too many daytime signals and thus deeming them unsuitable for nighttime use (",{"xref":1103,":@":1106},[1104],{"#text":1105},"Tosini et al., 2016",{"@_ref-type":794,"@_rid":1107},"B38",{"#text":1109},"). Here I will demonstrate that the contrary is true and in fact, there exists a fundamental dip in the melanopic region (from 470 to 500 nm) due to the way LED white light spectrum is generated. This means that white LEDs actually perform poorly when it comes to producing the necessary melanopic stimulation relative to its perceived color temperature and visual brightness.",{"#text":773},{"sec":1112,":@":2005},[1113,1114,1118,1119,1170,1171,1354,1355,1515,1516,1676,1677,1681,1682,1690,1691,1728,1729,1754,1755,1787,1788,1820,1821,1883,1884,1944,1945,1948,1949,1962,1963,1974,1975,2004],{"#text":706},{"title":1115},[1116],{"#text":1117},"Color Matching Functions",{"#text":706},{"p":1120},[1121,1123,1130,1132,1136,1138,1141,1143,1147,1148,1152,1154,1158,1160,1163,1165,1168],{"#text":1122},"Color matching functions shown in ",{"xref":1124,":@":1127},[1125],{"#text":1126},"Supplementary Figure 1",{"@_ref-type":1128,"@_rid":1129},"supplementary-material","FS1",{"#text":1131}," are used to convert any spectral power distribution to a (",{"italic":1133},[1134],{"#text":1135},"x,y",{"#text":1137},") point on the CIE 1931 color space diagram. These (",{"italic":1139},[1140],{"#text":1135},{"#text":1142},") color points are how the lighting industry communicates color. When referring to white light, these color coordinates are binned based on the temperature of a black body radiator in Kelvin (referred to as K). The following equations are used to convert spectrum into Tristimulus ",{"italic":1144},[1145],{"#text":1146},"X",{"#text":1093},{"italic":1149},[1150],{"#text":1151},"Y",{"#text":1153},", and ",{"italic":1155},[1156],{"#text":1157},"Z",{"#text":1159},", then to color coordinates (",{"italic":1161},[1162],{"#text":1135},{"#text":1164},"). Tristimulus ",{"italic":1166},[1167],{"#text":1151},{"#text":1169}," is also the luminous efficiency function, used to calculate lumens.",{"#text":706},{"disp-formula":1172,":@":1352},[1173,1174,1351],{"#text":700},{"mml:math":1175,":@":1347},[1176,1178,1346],{"#text":1177},"\n            ",{"mml:mrow":1179},[1180,1182,1192,1193,1197,1198,1345],{"#text":1181},"\n              ",{"mml:mpadded":1183,":@":1190},[1184,1186,1189],{"#text":1185},"\n                ",{"mml:mi":1187},[1188],{"#text":1146},{"#text":1181},{"@_width":1191},"+5.6pt",{"#text":1181},{"mml:mo":1194},[1195],{"#text":1196},"=",{"#text":1181},{"mml:mrow":1199},[1200,1201,1264,1265,1344],{"#text":1185},{"mml:munderover":1202},[1203,1205,1210,1211,1246,1247,1263],{"#text":1204},"\n                  ",{"mml:mo":1206,":@":1209},[1207],{"#text":1208},"∑",{"@_movablelimits":359},{"#text":1204},{"mml:mrow":1212},[1213,1215,1221,1222,1225,1226,1245],{"#text":1214},"\n                    ",{"mml:mi":1216,":@":1219},[1217],{"#text":1218},"λ",{"@_mathvariant":1220},"normal",{"#text":1214},{"mml:mo":1223},[1224],{"#text":1196},{"#text":1214},{"mml:mrow":1227},[1228,1230,1234,1235,1244],{"#text":1229},"\n                      ",{"mml:mn":1231},[1232],{"#text":1233},"380",{"#text":1229},{"mml:mrow":1236},[1237,1239,1243],{"#text":1238},"\n                        ",{"mml:mtext":1240},[1241],{"#text":1242},"nm",{"#text":1229},{"#text":1214},{"#text":1204},{"#text":1204},{"mml:mrow":1248},[1249,1250,1254,1255,1262],{"#text":1214},{"mml:mn":1251},[1252],{"#text":1253},"780",{"#text":1214},{"mml:mrow":1256},[1257,1258,1261],{"#text":1229},{"mml:mtext":1259},[1260],{"#text":1242},{"#text":1214},{"#text":1204},{"#text":1185},{"#text":1185},{"mml:mrow":1266},[1267,1268,1272,1273,1291,1292,1307,1308,1324,1325,1343],{"#text":1204},{"mml:mi":1269},[1270],{"#text":1271},"S",{"#text":1204},{"mml:mrow":1274},[1275,1276,1280,1281,1285,1286,1290],{"#text":1214},{"mml:mo":1277},[1278],{"#text":1279},"(",{"#text":1214},{"mml:mi":1282,":@":1284},[1283],{"#text":1218},{"@_mathvariant":1220},{"#text":1214},{"mml:mo"